Cross-Cloud Lifecycle Strategy for Replicated Buckets

(Oracle Cloud Infrastructure Object Storage ↔ Google Cloud Storage)

⸻

Problem Statement

The organization maintains bi-directional disaster recovery (DR) replication between:
	•	OCI — Primary Data Center
	•	GCP — Secondary Data Center (becomes Primary during failover)

Two bucket categories exist with different retention requirements:

1. Operational Buckets (Short Retention)
	•	Archive after 14 days
	•	Delete after 22 days

2. Core Banking Buckets (Compliance Retention)
	•	Archive for minimum 1 year
	•	No deletion allowed

If lifecycle policies are defined only on OCI:
	•	Storage tier mismatch occurs
	•	Retention becomes inconsistent
	•	DR failover leads to unpredictable behavior
	•	Storage costs may increase
	•	Compliance risks arise

Important:
Cloud lifecycle engines operate independently. Replication tools do not automatically replicate lifecycle policies or translate storage tiers.

⸻

Storage Tier Differences

OCI Object Storage Tiers
	•	Standard Tier
	•	Frequent access
	•	Immediate retrieval
	•	Archive Tier
	•	Low-cost cold storage
	•	Requires restore before access
	•	Designed for long-term retention

⸻

GCP Cloud Storage Classes
	•	Standard
	•	Frequent access
	•	Nearline
	•	Infrequent access (fast retrieval)
	•	Coldline
	•	Very infrequent access
	•	Lower cost than Nearline
	•	Archive
	•	Long-term retention
	•	Lowest cost
	•	365-day minimum storage billing

⸻

Requirement 1 — Operational Buckets (Short-Term Retention)

Lifecycle Objective
	•	Frequent access initially
	•	Move to low-cost storage after 14 days
	•	Automatic deletion after 22 days

Recommended Lifecycle Mapping

|| Requirement || OCI Policy || Recommended GCP Policy ||
| Frequent access | Standard Tier | Standard Class |
| Low-cost storage after 14 days | Archive Tier | Coldline Class |
| Delete after 22 days | Delete Rule | Delete Rule |

Why Coldline Instead of GCP Archive?
	•	GCP Archive has 365-day minimum billing
	•	Not cost-effective for short retention
	•	Coldline provides better cost alignment with OCI Archive for short-lived data

⸻

Requirement 2 — Core Banking Buckets (Long-Term Compliance Retention)

Lifecycle Objective
	•	Preserve data for at least 1 year
	•	Prevent accidental deletion
	•	Meet audit and regulatory requirements
	•	Ensure recoverability during DR failover

Recommended Lifecycle Mapping

|| Requirement || OCI Policy || Corresponding GCP Policy ||
| Frequent access (initial) | Standard Tier | Standard Class |
| Long-term archival | Move to Archive Tier after defined age | Move to Archive Storage Class after same age |
| Object deletion | No delete rule | No delete rule |

Why GCP Archive Is Suitable?
	•	Designed for long-term cold storage
	•	365-day minimum billing aligns with compliance needs
	•	Closest equivalent to OCI Archive tier

⸻

Root Cause of Cross-Cloud Lifecycle Drift

Replication tools typically:
	•	Copy object data
	•	Copy metadata
	•	Do not convert storage tier semantics
	•	Do not replicate lifecycle rules

Therefore, lifecycle intent must be configured separately on each cloud.

⸻

Final Recommendations
	•	Define lifecycle policies independently in both clouds
	•	Map tiers based on retention intent, not tier names
	•	Validate replication behavior for delete synchronization
	•	Test DR failover scenarios for:
	•	Data availability
	•	Application behavior
	•	Retention compliance
	•	Monitor storage cost impact across both clouds

⸻

Conclusion

Proper lifecycle alignment ensures:
	•	Predictable disaster recovery behavior
	•	Regulatory compliance
	•	Consistent retention posture
	•	Optimized storage cost
	•	No unexpected data loss

Failure to align lifecycle policies can result in:
	•	Retention drift
	•	Cost overruns
	•	Compliance violations
	•	Operational risk during failover
